Misuta Contrary Pancake is 100% correct that the biggest fault of people "into conspiracy theories", revisionist history, CIA crime affairs, etc. is that for some reason they always assume a "fatalistic" disposition instead of treating it like a fun side hobby. Cheer up a little!

Soylennial leftists whining "they killed JFK man, the billionaires won dude, there's nothing to do lol" are the obvious example, but even older right-wingers get into "whites are getting invaded, it's the Kalergi plan to genocide us" hysterics. A very unproductive, dull attitude.

Maybe Mozart and Goethe are correct that we ought to be a little more jovial. Maybe Mr. Kalergi added a fun secret plot twist at the end to surprise us. Or JFK was about to nuke Germany. But depression, hysterics are unnecessary when one is in no danger, just reading forum posts.
We do it at least as often as the rest if not more, we just treat eventual salvation as a sort of deus ex machina

Secrecy can cause an optical illusion of intelligence. One is tempted to imagine various "occult" think tanks, institutes as harboring evil geniuses, but in all likelihood it's people peddling inanities to each other that would be "slain clean" in an open debate with an outsider.

I think people generally underestimate the tendency of any secretive, unaccountable-to-anyone group to sink into a pleasant Brezhnevian corruption and complacency. If you're a well-paid military think tank, it's probably easy to figure out how to get money without doing anything.
The Lebowski Theorem applied to consulting groups and state agencies and etc.
